In [[computer science]], more particularly in [[formal language theory]], a '''cyclic language''' is a set of strings that is closed with respect to repetition, root, and [[cyclic shift#Applications|cyclic shift]].
==Definition== If ''A'' is a set of symbols, and ''A''<sup>[[Kleene star|*]]</sup> is the set of all strings built from symbols in ''A'', then a string set ''L'' ⊆ ''A''<sup>*</sup> is called a [[formal language]] over the [[Alphabet (formal languages)|alphabet]] ''A''. The language ''L'' is called ''cyclic'' if # ∀''w''∈''A''<sup>*</sup>. ∀''n''>0. ''w'' ∈ ''L'' ⇔ ''w''<sup>''n''</sup> ∈ ''L'', and # ∀''v'',''w''∈''A''<sup>*</sup>. ''vw'' ∈ ''L'' ⇔ ''wv'' ∈ ''L'', where ''w''<sup>''n''</sup> denotes the ''n''-fold repetition of the string ''w'', and ''vw'' denotes the [[concatenation]] of the strings ''v'' and ''w''.<ref name="Beal.Carton.Reutenauer.1996">{{cite book | contributionurl=http://www.lacim.uqam.ca/~christo/Publi%C3%A9s/1996/Strongly%20cyclic%20languages.pdf | author=Marie-Pierre Béal and Olivier Carton and Christophe Reutenauer | contribution=Cyclic Languages and Strongly Cyclic Languages | editor= | title=Proc. [[Symposium on Theoretical Aspects of Computer Science]] | publisher=Springer | series=[[Lecture Notes in Computer Science]] | volume=1046 | pages=49&ndash;59 | year=1996 }}</ref>{{rp|Def.1}}
==Examples== For example, using the alphabet ''A'' = {''a'', ''b'' }, the language {| |- | ALIGN=RIGHT | ''L'' = | { | | ''a''<sup>''p''</sup>''b''<sup>''n''<sub>1</sub></sup> | ''a''<sup>''n''<sub>2</sub></sup>''b''<sup>''n''<sub>2</sub></sup> | ... | ''a''<sup>''n''<sub>''k''</sub></sup>''b''<sup>''n''<sub>''k''</sub></sup> | ''a''<sup>''q''</sup> | : | ''n''<sub>''i''</sub> ≥ 0 and ''p''+''q'' = ''n''<sub>1</sub> } |- | ALIGN=RIGHT | ∪ | { | ''b''<sup>''p''</sup> | ''a''<sup>''n''<sub>1</sub></sup>''b''<sup>''n''<sub>1</sub></sup> | ''a''<sup>''n''<sub>2</sub></sup>''b''<sup>''n''<sub>2</sub></sup> | ... | ''a''<sup>''n''<sub>''k''</sub></sup> ''b''<sup>''q''</sup> | | : | ''n''<sub>''i''</sub> ≥ 0 and ''p''+''q'' = ''n''<sub>''k''</sub> } |} is cyclic, but not [[regular language|regular]].<ref name="Beal.Carton.Reutenauer.1996"/>{{rp|Exm.2}} However, ''L'' is [[context-free language|context-free]], since ''M'' = { ''a''<sup>''n''<sub>1</sub></sup>''b''<sup>''n''<sub>1</sub></sup> ''a''<sup>''n''<sub>2</sub></sup>''b''<sup>''n''<sub>2</sub></sup> ... ''a''<sup>''n''<sub>''k''</sub></sup> ''b''<sup>''n''<sub>''k''</sub></sup> : ''n''<sub>''i''</sub> ≥ 0 } is, and context-free languages are closed under [[circular shift#Applications|circular shift]]; ''L'' is obtained as circular shift of ''M''.
