[[File:Frederick William Kahapula Beckley (1874–1943).jpg|thumb|Frederick William Kahapula Beckley]]
'''Frederick William Kahapula Beckley Jr.''' (May 7, 1874 – December 20, 1943) was a [[Native Hawaiians|Native Hawaiian]] politician, historian, and educator. He was the last official interpreter of the [[Supreme Court of Hawaii|Hawaii Supreme Court]] during the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]] and was the first professor of [[Hawaiian language]] at the [[University of Hawaii]].

==Biography==
He was born on May 7, 1874, in Honolulu, the son of [[Frederick William Kahapula Beckley Sr.]] and [[Emma Kaili Metcalf Beckley Nakuina|Emma Kaili Metcalf]]. He was descended from chiefly lineages from both his parents, and his ancestors included High Chief [[Hoolulu|Hoʻolulu]] and Captain [[George Charles Beckley]], both advisors of King [[Kamehameha I]]. His father died in 1881 and his mother remarried in 1887 to Moses Kuea Nakuina, who became Beckley's stepfather.{{sfn|Bacchilega|2011|pages=108–112}} At an early age, he became interested in [[Hawaiian language]] and [[History of Hawaii|history]]. He was educated at [[Saint Louis School]], [[Kamehameha Schools]], and [[Punahou School|Oahu College]].<ref name="Nellist1925"/>

Beckley served as the last official interpreter of the [[Supreme Court of Hawaii|Supreme Court]] prior to the [[Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii]].<ref name="Nellist1925"/> Afterward, he continued working as a translator and was interpreter for the [[Territory of Hawaii]]'s First Circuit Court from 1906 to 1914. In 1900, he ran for the Hawaii Territorial House of Representatives representing [[Maui]] as a candidate of the [[Home Rule Party of Hawaii|Home Rule Party]], founded by former royalist revolutionary [[Robert William Wilcox]].{{sfn|Bacchilega|2011|pages=111–112}}<ref name="Nellist1925"/><ref name="office">{{cite web |url= http://archives1.dags.hawaii.gov/gsdl/collect/governme/import/import/Government%20Office%20Holders%20-%20Name%20IMJ/B/Beckley,%20Fredrick%20W%20Jr.jpg|title= Beckley, Fredrick W Jr. office record |work=state archives digital collections |publisher=state of Hawaii |accessdate= May 13, 2012}}</ref> While in the legislature, he served as Vice-Speaker in 1901 and 1902 was [[List of Speakers of the Hawaii House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] from 1903 to 1904.{{sfn|Hawaii|Lydecker|1918|pages=263–271}} He later joined the [[Hawaii Republican Party]].{{sfn|Bacchilega|2011|pages=111–112}}

In later life, he became an educator. He taught Hawaiian history and language at [[President William McKinley High School|McKinley High School]] and served as the first professor of Hawaiian language at the [[University of Hawaii]] in 1922.<ref name="Nellist1925"/>{{sfn|Bacchilega|2011|pages=111–112}}

He married Alice L. K. Heanu on October 2, 1902. They had nine children.<ref name="Nellist1925">{{cite book|last=Nellist|first=George F. M.|chapter=Frederick William Beckley|title=Men of Hawaii|url=http://files.usgwarchives.net/hi/statewide/bios/beckley143bs.txt|volume=3|year=1925|publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|oclc=153923202}}</ref> Beckley died on December 20, 1943.{{sfn|Ritter|1989|page=47}}

