{{Infobox language |name=Karuk |altname=Karok |region=Northwestern [[California]], United States |ethnicity=[[Karuk people|Karuk]] |speakers=12 |revived=30 [[L2 speakers]] (2007) |date=2007 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Hokan languages|Hokan]] ? |iso3=kyh |map=Karuk lang.png |mapcaption= |notice=IPA |glotto=karo1304 |glottorefname=Karok }}
'''Karuk''' or '''Karok''' is an [[endangered language]] of northwestern [[California]]. It is the traditional language of the [[Karuk]] people, most of whom now speak English. The name is derived from the word ''Káruk'', which means 'upriver'.<ref name="Campbell">{{cite book|author=Lyle Campbell|title=American Indian Languages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h36tPYqAZPwC|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-534983-2}}</ref>{{rp|397}}
==History and usage== The Karuk language originated around the Klamath River between [[Seiad Valley, California|Seiad Valley]] and Bluff Creek. Prior to [[Europe]]an contact, it is estimated that there may have been up to 1,500 speakers.<ref name=":03"/> Linguist [[William Bright]] documented the Karuk language and when Bright began his studies in 1949 there were "a couple of hundred fluent speakers," but by 2011, there were fewer than a dozen fluent elders.<ref name="Walters">{{cite news|last=Walters|first=Heidi|title=In Karuk: A family struggles to bring its ancestral tongue back to life|url=http://www.northcoastjournal.com/humboldt/in-karuk/Content?oid=2132629|accessdate=October 4, 2013|newspaper=North Coast Journal|date=October 27, 2011}}</ref> A standardized system for writing the languages was adopted in the 1980s.<ref name = "e18" />
==Classification== Karuk is a language isolate, sharing few if any similarities with other nearby languages. Historically, the American linguist [[Edward Sapir]] proposed it be classified as part of the [[Hokan languages|Hokan family]] he hypothesized although little evidence supports this proposal.<ref name="Campbell" /> As Bright wrote, "The Karok language is not closely or obviously related to any other (in the area), but has been classified as a member of the northern group of Hokan languages, in a subgroup which includes Chimariko and the Shasta languages, spoken in the same general part of California as Karok itself."<ref name="Bright1957">{{cite book|author=William Bright|title=The Karok Language, by William Bright|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cqxLYAAACAAJ|year=1957|publisher=University of California Press}}</ref>
== Geographic distribution == Karuk is spoken within the range of the original territory where the Karuk people lived prior to [[Europe]]an contact. The ancestral territory is in Northwestern California existing in [[Siskiyou County, California|Siskiyou]], [[Humboldt County, California|Humboldt]], and [[Del Norte County, California|Del Norte]] counties.<ref name=":6">{{Cite web|url=http://karuk.org/territorymap.shtml|title=Karuk Ancestral Territory Map - Karuk Language Resources on the Web|last=Gehr|first=Susan|website=karuk.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-30}}</ref> The language originated around the [[Klamath River]] between [[Seiad Valley, California|Seiad Valley]] and Bluff Creek. Karuk is most notably found in towns [[Somes Bar, California|Somes Bar]], which is near The Karuk Center of the World (in Karuk, "Katimiin"), [[Happy Camp, California|Happy Camp]] ("Athithufvuunupma"), and [[Orleans, California|Orleans]] ("Panamniik").<ref name=":6" />
==Phonology==
===Vowels=== {| class="IPA wikitable" style="text-align: center;" ! rowspan=2| ! colspan=2|[[Front vowel|Front]] ! colspan=2|[[Central vowel|Central]] !colspan=2| [[Back vowel|Back]] |- !<small>short</small> !<small>long</small> !<small>short</small> !<small>long</small> !<small>short</small> !<small>long</small> |- ! [[Close vowel|Close]] | i || iː | || | u || uː |- ! [[Mid vowel|Mid]] | || eː | || | || oː |- ! [[Open vowel|Open]] | || | a || aː | || |} There are only 5 [[vowel]]s in Karuk, as shown by the chart, where ''a'', ''i'', and ''u'' have both long and short forms, while ''e'' and ''o'' are in the long form.<ref name=":03">{{Cite web|url=http://linguistics.berkeley.edu/~survey/languages/karuk.php|title=Karuk – Survey of California and Other Indian Languages|website=linguistics.berkeley.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>
===Consonants=== {| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;" ! ! [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ! [[Labiodental consonant|Labiodental]] ! [[Dental consonant|Dental]] ! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! [[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- ! [[Nasal stop|Nasal]] | {{IPA|m}} | | | {{IPA|n}} | | | | |- ! [[Stop consonant|Stop]] | {{IPA|p}} | | | {{IPA|t}} | {{IPA|t͡ʃ}} | | {{IPA|k}} | {{IPA|ʔ}} |- ! [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] | {{IPA|β}} | {{IPA|f}} | {{IPA|θ}} | {{IPA|s}} | {{IPA|(ʃ)}} | | {{IPA|x}} | {{IPA|h}} |- ! [[Flap consonant|Flap]] | | | | {{IPA|ɾ}} | | | | |- ! [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | | | | |{{IPA|j}} | | |} Karuk only has 16 consonants, a small compared to the relatively large consonant inventories of most California languages.<ref name=":03"/> Karuk also does not show any modifications to its consonants like glottalization or labialization, also unusual for a California language.
=== Syllabification === When two high vowels are juxtaposed in a word, then the first vowel turns into a [[Glide (vowel)|glide]] in the following examples.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/|title=Phonemic vs. derived glides|last=Levi|first=Susannah|date=27 September 2008|website=ScienceDirect|access-date=}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" !First Vowel !Glide Transition !English Translation |- |imuira |imwira |fishery |- |imiuha |imjúha |soap plant |- |suniiθih |sunjíθih |nut of a giant chinquapin |} ''Note: Syllabification in these examples are from right-to-left.''<ref name=":2" />
The following example is a more rare case in Karuk where the [[syllabification]] is from left-to-right.<ref name=":2" /> {| class="wikitable" !First Vowel !Glide Transition !English Translation |- |uiriwsaw |wíriwʃaw |to bequeath to |}
==Grammar==
=== General === Karuk is a [[polysynthetic language]] known for its method of arranging old and new information: "... skilled Karuk speakers use separate words to communicate new, salient detail, or to underscore known detail; and they use affixes for background details so that a listener's attention is not diverted."<ref name="SilverMiller1997">{{cite book|author1=Shirley Silver|author2=Wick R. Miller|title=American Indian languages: cultural and social contexts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dAiDAAAAIAAJ|year=1997|publisher=University of Arizona Press|isbn=978-0-8165-1802-9}}</ref>{{rp|41}}
=== Morphology === Karuk is similar to many other [[American Indian languages|American Indian Languages]] because "verbs bear a complex person-marking system, where subject and object are marked in portmanteau [[prefix]]es."<ref name=":03"/> Depending on the subject and the object the speaker is referring to, there is a prefix for both positive and negative indicatives, as well as a prefix for the potential mood. Through his research, [[William Bright]] found there to insufficient words to describe [[cardinal direction]]s, but the language uses [[suffix]]es on verbs to describe relevant direction. Many motion verbs have a singular and plural form. Through [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphology]], long-form vowels are used when ''a'' is next to ''i'' or ''u''. Karuk uses accents where vowels can sound differently in each word, making the language difficult to learn.<ref name=":03" /> Although the structure may be similar, Karuk is considered to be much different than its neighboring languages, such as [[Yurok language|Yurok]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED282688.pdf|title=American Indian Bilingual Education|last=Bennett|first=Ruth|date=1 March 1987|website=eric.ed.gov|access-date=}}</ref>
=== Verbs === Karuk uses prefixes and suffixes in a way [[William Bright]] relates to how English words ''snort'', ''sniff'', and ''sneeze'' all start with a ''sn-''. The following are examples of prefixes in Karuk.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Macaulay|first=Monica|date=1993-01-01|title=Reduplication and the Structure of the Karuk Verb Stem|jstor=1265470|journal=International Journal of American Linguistics|volume=59|issue=1|pages=64–81|doi=10.1086/466185}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" !Karuk !English Translation |- |'''''im-''''' |'''<nowiki/>'involving heat or fire'''' |- |impat |'to become broken due to heat' |- |imčak |'to get burnt' |- |imčax |'to be hot' |- |'''ʔak-''' |'''<nowiki/>'with the hand'''' |- |ʔaknup |'to thump' |- |ʔaktuṽ |'to pluck at' |- |akxárap |'to scratch' |}
== Words and phrases == {| class="wikitable" |+From Dr. William Bright's research<ref name=":32">{{Cite web|url=http://linguistics.berkeley.edu/~karuk/karuk-texts.php?speaker-page=WB|title=Ararahih'urípih|website=linguistics.berkeley.edu|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> !Karuk !English Translation |- |'''xâatik vaa ukupítih''' |Let it do that |- |'''kári xás pihnêefich upiip, pûuhara.''' |Then coyote said, "no." |- |'''pihnêefich''' |coyote |- |'''túuyship''' |mountain |- |'''koovúra yúruk kámvuunupahitih.''' |Let it all flow downstream. |} ''Note: More translations can be found online in the Dictionary section depicting Dr. Bright's research.'' {| class="wikitable" |+From Phil Albers, Jr.'s work<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.karuk.us/index.php/departments/language-program/karuk-words|title=Karuk Words|last=Albers Jr.|first=Phil|date=|website=www.karuk.us|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> !Karuk !English Translation |- |'''hãa''' |yes |- |'''pûuhara''' |no |- |'''ta'ávahiv''' |time to eat |- |'''íikam''' |it's time to go outside |- |'''ka'íru''' |be quiet/quiet down |}
== Revitalization efforts ==
=== Dr. William Bright === Dr. [[William Bright]] started studying the Karuk language in 1949 in pursuit of his doctorate in [[linguistics]] at [[U.C. Berkeley|U.C Berkeley]]. Bright was met with open arms by tribal elders and was taken in and called '''Uhyanapatánvaanich''', or "little word-asker" in Karuk.<ref name=":32"/> A little under a decade later, Bright published ''The Karok Language''&nbsp;(University of California), which was a highly informative piece on the Karuk language, its grammar, and [[syntax]].<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/23/books/23bright.html|title=William Bright, 78, Expert in Indigenous Languages, Is Dead|last=Fox|first=Margalit|date=2006-10-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-04-29|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Bright worked with Susan Gehr, a tribe member and fellow linguist, on a Karuk [[dictionary]], which was published in 2005.<ref name=":4" /> Bright was a different type of linguist because he did not see language without cultural context. He would record everyday conversations, songs, stories, and poetry of fluent Karuk speakers to attempt to capture the language and what it meant to those speaking it.<ref name=":4" /> He spent over fifty years studying, researching, and documenting Karuk, and is the only non-Indian to be inducted as an honorary member of the tribe thanks to his contributions to the community. Bright was buried on Karuk land when he died in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northcoastjournal.com/humboldt/in-karuk/Content?oid=2132629|title=In Karuk|last=Walters|first=Heidi|website=North Coast Journal|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>
=== Revival through education ===
==== American Indian Bilingual Teacher Credential Program ==== In the late 1980s, [[Humboldt State University]] started the "American Indian Bilingual Teacher Credential Program", where they brought in teachers from four local tribes, being the [[Hupa]], [[Yurok]], [[Karuk]], and [[Tolowa]].<ref name=":12">{{Cite web|url=http://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED282688.pdf|title=American Indian Bilingual Education|last=Bennett|first=Ruth|date=1 March 1987|website=eric.ed.gov|access-date=}}</ref> These teachers were bilingual in their tribe's native language as well as [[English language|English]], and would be employed in local public schools to teach American Indian children. The university developed this initiative to help local [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian]] populations either further develop their English for higher education or improve upon their native language to preserve culture. Bilingual teachers in both Karuk and English would teach [[Orleans, California|Orleans]] Elementary and [[Happy Camp, California|Happy Camp]] Elementary, where children would learn how to live in America while keeping their identity.<ref name=":12" />
=== Karuk Language Restoration Committee === In 1990, attempts were made to revive the language by The Karuk&nbsp;Language&nbsp;Restoration Committee. This committee, composed of eight volunteers, drafted a 5-year minimum plan in attempt to preserve the Karuk language and help it grow in the future.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?sid=7a944d7f-ed00-4fe1-96f0-31f96d38359a%40sessionmgr4008&vid=0&hid=4208&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZSZzY29wZT1zaXRl#AN=9610253548&db=a9h|title=Karuk Language Restoration Committee nearing completion of five-year plan.|last=Burcell-Price|first=Suzanne|date=30 August 1990|website=Ebscohost|access-date=}}</ref> The committee was also advised by Dr. [[William Bright]] and tribal member Julian Lang, a dedicated researcher of the language. Their studies showed that the decline of the language is caused by a combination of a lack of younger fluent speakers, the number of speakers is falling in general, it is not typically taught at home at young ages, it is not flexible to be modernized, and most tribal members cannot read the Karuk language.<ref name=":5" />
The committee ultimately created a five-step plan:<ref name=":5" /> # Recording and writing down fluent speakers communicating in Karuk. # Training more people to become fluent for a long-term goal. # Teaching tribal members and local communities why learning the language is vital to not only the language, but also to the culture. # Reviewing and receiving community feedback regarding the current plan. # Facilitating the community to participate in programs that have people practice and speak Karuk.
